      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i need help with this python function for my uni coding lab. the grader is super strict about the time limit and it keeps failing my submission because the complexity is too high for large inputs. can u optimize it so it passes the runtime tests? thanks.\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    temp = n\n    while temp > 1:\n        while temp % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            temp //= d\n        d += 1\n    return factors\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue with your code is that it checks every number up to `n` to see if it's a factor, which results in a time complexity of O(n). We can optimize this to O(sqrt(n)) by only checking up to the square root of `n`.\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    while d * d <= n:  # only need to check up to sqrt(n)\n        while n % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 1\n    if n > 1:  # if n is still greater than 1, it's a prime factor\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\n\nThis code works by only checking up to the square root of `n` because a larger factor of `n` would be a multiple of a smaller factor that has already been checked. This significantly reduces the time complexity for large inputs.",
